## Plot R² vs Distance

This plot will help you see whether sensor pairs that are closer together tend to have stronger agreement (higher R²).
Each point represents a pair of devices, and the R² measures how similarly they track daily PM2.5 concentrations.
```{r}
library(ggplot2)
library(ggpmisc)

ggplot(r2_distance_df, aes(x = distance_m / 1000, y = r2)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "gray30", linetype = "dashed", size = 0.8) +
  stat_poly_eq(aes(label = paste(..rr.label.., sep = "~~~")),
               formula = y ~ x,
               parse = TRUE,
               label.x = "right",
               label.y = 0.95,
               size = 5,
               color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Relationship Between Sensor Distance and R² 
                             (CinC PM2.5)",
    x = "Distance Between Devices (km)",
    y = expression(R^2 * " of Daily PM2.5")
  ) +
  xlim(0, 25) +
  ylim(0, 1) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 16)

```

Interpretation:

	•	As the distance between sensors increases, the R² tends to decrease slightly.
	•	This means that closer sensors generally show more similar PM2.5 readings on a day-to-day basis.
	•	The overall fit of the linear trend is quite weak (only 10% of the variance in R² is explained by distance).
	•	This implies distance is not the only factor — other influences like local emission sources, wind patterns, or sensor quality may also impact agreement between sites.
	•	There’s a wide range of R² values even among sensors that are close together.
	•	This suggests some close sensors still measure differently, perhaps due to micro-environmental effects.

